Now then let us consider these 20 billion MT photon torpedos.<br>
<br>
Let us igjnore the fact that, because of the dialogue, it is impossible to preform even ballpark calcs.  Let us ignore the fact that we have never seen frepower anywhere close to this level elsewhere.  Let us ignore the fact that if you packed in enoough antimatter to get that blast, the torpedo would be too large to fit into the launcher.  Let us ignore the fact that he is yet to post the source of these ubercalcs.  Let us ignore the fact that his theory to explain the visuals has absoultly zero backing because torpedos are not focused explosives and lack armor piercing capabilities.<br>
<br>
Let us simply consider the math.<br>
<br>
THe objective of the mission was to reduce the planet to it's molten core.  his was to take 5 hours and would require a fleet of 20 ships.  Now even though we see ships firing 2 torpedos per second per launcher plus disruptors, let us simplify the calcs by saying that each ship fired only one torpedo per second.<br>
<br>
5 hours = 5 * 60 * 60 = 18000 seconds for the operation.<br>
20 billion MT = 2^16 tons<br>
20 ships firing once per second * 2^16 tons per torpedo = 4^17 tons per second<br>
4^17 * 18000 seconds = 7.2^21 total tons.<br>
4.186^9 = 1 ton<br>
<br>
This gives us a total energy of 3.01392^31 joules.<br>
<br>
This will not redue the planet to it's mantle, it will vaporize the thing.  Clearly the calcs are just someone's little pipe dream..  And frankly, on a forum dedicated to real science and its use in the space movement, I am suprised no one bothered to preform basic mathmatics and simple unit conversions to disprove these calcs before me.<br>
<br>
<br>
Now then, how about some accurate ST calcs?  In <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Enterprise</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, the phase cannon or Type 1 phaser are canonically stated to have a yield of 500 GJ.  Since phasers double in power each type they are, this means that the output for type 12 phasers mounted on the E-E are 1.024^15, or a piddling little 245 KT.  From TNG's <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Pegasus</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, simple volume, energy transfer and heat of vaporization calcs produce a yield of 500 KT for photon torps.<br>
<br>
So go ahead and use a tactic long since lost to the Federation.  You still won't even darken the paint on a Star Destroyer. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uxalev.showPublicProfile?language=EN>XaLEv</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_lightning.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 7<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(9/11/02 8:06:06 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=63.topic&index=28>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.geocities.com/scythe523/ratface2.txt WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: ST vs. SW</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I believe his point is that TOS (the ORIGINAL SERIES) is canon, which means a sanctioned or accepted group or body of related works<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
